line=279 fonts=F0-14.0 bbox=56.68,520.2,226.22,534.24                     :Conclusions  and  Speculations
line=280 fonts=F0-13.0 bbox=56.68,499.08,483.88,512.04 iscore=0.10        :Inverse systems are ingenious in reference-tracking, but have some disadvantages:
line=281 fonts=F0-13.0,F4-13.0 bbox=74.68,483.2,538.66,496.2 iscore=0.09  :   •   are computationally complex  (need relative salience features rather than absolute
line=282 fonts=F0-13.0 bbox=92.68,468.24,171.16,481.2 iscore=0.10         :       person values),
line=283 fonts=F0-13.0,F4-13.0 bbox=74.68,452.36,406.16,465.36 iscore=0.10:   •   require salience differences even when they are not obvious,
line=284 fonts=F0-13.0,F4-13.0 bbox=74.68,436.4,353.22,449.4 iscore=0.20  :   •   block certain generalizations over similar settings,
line=285 fonts=F0-13.0,F4-13.0 bbox=74.68,420.56,358.64,433.56 iscore=0.29:   •   can distinguish syntactic arguments only indirectly.
line=286 fonts=F0-13.0 bbox=56.68,399.48,357.18,412.44 iscore=0.12        :Inverse(-like) systems, as found in many languages today:
line=287 fonts=F0-13.0,F4-13.0 bbox=74.68,383.6,298.12,396.6 iscore=0.14  :   •   are often mixed and redundant systems,
line=288 fonts=F0-13.0,F4-13.0 bbox=74.68,367.76,326.84,380.76 iscore=0.29:   •   have many portmanteau  or lexicalized forms,
line=289 fonts=F0-13.0,F4-13.0 bbox=74.68,351.92,345.08,364.92 iscore=0.30:   •   are often merged with active type sets of affixes,
line=290 fonts=F0-13.0,F4-13.0 bbox=74.68,335.96,497.47,348.96 iscore=0.33:   •   have often acquired in addition a case system (which mostly is a split system),
line=291 fonts=F0-13.0,F4-13.0 bbox=74.68,320.12,509.11,333.12 iscore=0.47:   •   often exhibit gaps or specialized operations in the realization of inverse settings.
line=292 fonts=F0-13.0 bbox=56.68,299.16,441.06,312.12 iscore=0.15        :Inverse systems are exclusively found in languages with rich morphology:
line=293 fonts=F0-13.0,F4-13.0 bbox=74.68,283.28,531.71,296.28 iscore=0.08:   •   inverse voice requires head-marking, whereas case marking is not restricted to heads
line=294 fonts=F0-13.0 bbox=56.68,262.2,538.63,275.16 iscore=0.08         :The  inherent logic of inverse systems (based on complementary   input settings) offers a
line=295 fonts=F0-13.0 bbox=56.68,247.2,349.87,260.16 iscore=0.15         :melting-pot for the evolution of several languages types:
line=296 fonts=F0-13.0,F4-13.0 bbox=74.68,231.32,356.35,244.32 iscore=0.00:   •   inheres already number (and obviative) agreement,
line=297 fonts=F0-13.0,F4-13.0 bbox=74.68,215.48,303.16,228.48 iscore=0.43:   •   enables case systems by reinterpretation,
line=298 fonts=F0-13.0,F4-13.0 bbox=74.68,199.63,275.2,212.64 iscore=0.50 :   •   enables passive by reinterpretation,
line=299 fonts=F0-13.0,F4-13.0 bbox=74.68,183.67,412.03,196.68 iscore=0.38:   •   enables cross-references between main and dependent clause,
line=300 fonts=F0-13.0,F4-13.0 bbox=74.68,167.83,498.64,180.84 iscore=0.25:   •   nearly every type of language is compatible with (redundant) inverse marking.
line=301 fonts=F0-13.0,F6-13.0 bbox=56.68,146.83,518.09,159.84 iscore=0.13:‣󿿻There  is a lot of evidence that inverse systems may have developed into case systems.
line=302 fonts=F0-13.0,F6-13.0 bbox=56.68,131.83,507.65,144.84 iscore=0.33:‣󿿻There  is no indication that a case system ever has developed into an inverse system.
line=303 fonts=F0-13.0,F6-13.0 bbox=56.68,110.83,538.68,123.84 iscore=0.07:‣󿿻An   inverse system requires to mark  relative salience in the context of abstract case.
line=304 fonts=F0-13.0 bbox=74.56,95.88,244.48,108.84 iscore=0.00         :   (computationally more complex)
line=305 fonts=F0-13.0,F6-13.0 bbox=56.68,80.83,529.3,93.84 iscore=0.07   :‣󿿻A  case system requires to mark abstract case in the context of specific salience features.
line=306 fonts=F0-13.0 bbox=73.72,65.88,361.86,78.84 iscore=0.21          :   (computationally simpler, has advantages in the syntax)

